'''Nicholas de Monchaux''' (born July 30, 1973) is a designer and author, and Professor of Architecture and Urban Design in the [[UC Berkeley College of Environmental Design|College of Environmental Design]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ced.berkeley.edu/ced/faculty-staff/nicholas-de-monchaux|title=Nicholas-de Monchaux|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> He is currently Director of the [[Berkeley Center for New Media]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bcnm.berkeley.edu/people/113/executive-comittee|title=Berkeley Center for New Media|website=bcnm.berkeley.edu|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> de Monchaux is the author of [https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/spacesuit Spacesuit: Fashioning Apollo],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/642351481|title=Spacesuit : fashioning Apollo|last=1973-|first=De Monchaux, Nicholas,|date=2011|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262015202|location=Cambridge, Mass.|oclc=642351481}}</ref> a cultural, physical, and intellectual history of the [[Apollo/Skylab A7L|Apollo A7L spacesuit]]; the book was winner of the [[Eugene M. Emme Astronautical Literature Award|Eugene Emme Astronautical Literature Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://astronautical.org/awards/emme/|title=Eugene M. Emme Astronautical Literature Awards {{!}} American Astronautical Society|website=astronautical.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> and Shortlisted for the [[Authors' Club|Author's Club Art Book (Sir Banister Fletcher) Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flint-pr.com/news/flint-client-news/the-art-book-prize-launches-at-the-whitechapel-gallery/|title=The Art Book Prize launches at the Whitechapel Gallery {{!}} Flint PR Agency UK|date=2012-10-11|access-date=2017-08-07|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011065347/http://www.flint-pr.com/news/flint-client-news/the-art-book-prize-launches-at-the-whitechapel-gallery/|archivedate=2012-10-11|df=}}</ref> In 2012 he was named as one of the [https://www.good.is/infographics/infographic-100-leaders-in-public-interest-design "Public Interest Design 100"];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.good.is/infographics/infographic-100-leaders-in-public-interest-design|title=Infographic: 100 Leaders in Public Interest Design|date=2012-12-08|work=GOOD Magazine|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en}}</ref> In 2016 he published [http://localco.de Local Code: 3,659 Proposals about Data, Design, and the Nature of Cities],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/925410808|title=Local code : 3,659 proposals about data, design & the nature of cities|last=1973-|first=De Monchaux, Nicholas,|isbn=9781616893804|edition=First|location=New York|oclc=925410808}}</ref> which combines several historical essays on urbanism, computing, and complexity with 3,659 designs for micro-scaled ecological interventions in San Francisco, Los Angeles, New York, and Venice Italy. This work has been praised by the New York Times for its "Intelligent enquiry and actionable theorizing,"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/space-its-still-a-frontier/|title=Space: It's Still a Frontier|last=Arieff|first=Allison|date=2010-02-10|website=Opinionator|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> and has been exhibited at the [[Biennial of the Americas]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/38265/Denver-Biennial-of-the-Americas-Announces-Inaugural-Exhibition#.WYiPONPyvMU|title=Denver Biennial of the Americas Announces Inaugural Exhibition|last=Villarreal|first=Ignacio|website=artdaily.com|language=en|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> the [[Venice Biennale of Architecture|Venice Architecture Biennale]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.archdaily.com/249209/u-s-pavilion-at-the-venice-architecture-biennale-announces-designers-and-participants|title=Venice Biennale 2012: U.S. Pavilion Announces Designers and Participants|date=2012-06-28|work=ArchDaily|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en-US}}</ref> The Lisbon Architecture Triennial,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.trienaldelisboa.com/theformofform/en/programa/the-world-in-our-eyes/|title=The World in Our Eyes {{!}} The Form of Form|work=The Form of Form|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> and [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SFMOMA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfmoma.org/press/release/sfmoma-looks-at-buckminster-fullers-legacy-in-the/|title=SFMOMA LOOKS AT BUCKMINSTER FULLER’S LEGACY IN THE BAY AREA|website=SFMOMA|language=en|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref>  He is a Fellow of the [[American Academy in Rome]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aarome.org/news/features/2013-14-rome-prize-winners-announced|title=Features {{!}} American Academy in Rome|website=www.aarome.org|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref>

